        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/QtTs8.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 72575,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 209513,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/209513/subhrajyoti-majumder",
                "reputation": 41328,
                "display_name": "Subhrajyoti Majumder",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1357883789,
            "creation_date": 1357883247,
            "body": "<p><code>this<\/code> refer to current Object, you can refer to any member of the current object from within an instance method or a constructor by using this. <strong>But you can not use <code>this<\/code> reference in static context(method or block)<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p><code>static<\/code> method can be called without creating object of that class. So if you use this or non-static variable into the static context it will create compilation error.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 14272441,
            "question_id": 14272376,
            "last_edit_date": 1357883789
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd866dcc00fd8002ddcf2303e6873e3d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1111134,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1101579,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1101579/claesv",
                "reputation": 2113,
                "display_name": "claesv",
                "accept_rate": 40
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1357887009,
            "creation_date": 1357883214,
            "body": "<p>You probably want to create instances of the classes, and turn the methods into instance methods rather than static methods.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class FirstClass {\n\n    private int idNo = 25;        \n\n    public void print() {\n        System.out.println(\"firstclass citizen \" + this.idNo);\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and then from the main method:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>FirstClass fc = new FirstClass();\nfc.print();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 14272439,
            "question_id": 14272376,
            "last_edit_date": 1357887009
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f51a5a13597896623ba922fd213dbf83?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2226867,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1965396,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1965396/william-seiti-mizuta",
                "reputation": 8045,
                "display_name": "William Seiti Mizuta"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1357883353,
            "creation_date": 1357883353,
            "body": "<p>You can't reference a non static attribute and use this into a static method, ie, <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class FirstClass\n{\n    static int idNo =25;\n    public static void print()\n    {\n            System.out.println(\"firstclass citizen \" + idNo);\n    }\n}\nclass SecondClass\n{\n    static int idNo =24;\n    public static void print()\n    {\n            System.out.println(\"secondclass citizen\" + idNo);\n    }\n}\npublic class People\n{\n    FirstClass female;\n    SecondClass male;\n    public static void main(String[] args)\n    {\n            System.out.println(\"people from java world\");\n            FirstClass.print();\n            SecondClass.print();\n   }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 14272457,
            "question_id": 14272376
        }
